Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @sweet potatoes{1} into ½-inch pieces. Quarter @lemon{1}.

Toss sweet potato on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{drizzle} and a pinch
of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack, tossing halfway through, until browned and tender,
~{20-25%minutes}.

While sweet potato roasts, in a #medium bowl{}, whisk together @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}, @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon}, juice from half the lemon, and @sugar{½%tsp}. Slowly drizzle in @olive oil{¼%cup}, whisking continuously until combined. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

In a second medium bowl, combine @ricotta cheese{4%ounce}, @panko breadcrumbs{¼%cup}, @Parmesan cheese{¼%cup}, half the @tempura batter{82%g}, @salt{¼%tsp}, and a pinch of pepper. Stir in @water{6%TBSP} until thoroughly combined.

Heat a 1⁄3-inch layer of @cooking oil{1/3-inch layer} in a #large, heavy-bottomed pan{}
over medium-high heat. Once oil is hot enough that a drop of batter sizzles when
added to pan, add scant ¼-cup scoops of batter and lightly press down with a
#spatula{} to form 6 ½-inch-thick fritters (12 for 4 servings). Cook until golden
brown and crisp, ~{2-3%minutes} per side. Transfer fritters to a #paper-towel-lined
plate{}.

> Don't overcrowd the pan; you may need to cook in batches!

In a #large bowl{}, toss @spinach{5%ounce} and sweet potato with as much dressing as you like. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide salad between bowls. Top with fritters and drizzle with any remaining dressing. Sprinkle with @sliced almonds{½%ounce} and serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side.